@@@ 1900 Data acquisition mode
Enter the number of the Data Acquisition (DA) 
Mode to be used. 

If you are not sure which built-in or custom DA
Mode to use, refer to the OMA 4000 manual.
@@@ 1901 Detector type (Setup screen)
The Detector type parameter field is used to 
indicate the type of detector being used. There
are basically two types of arrays available: Photo
Diode Array (PDA) and Charge-Coupled Device
(CCD). The detector and the detector controller
must be compatible. Check your detector manual
to determine the appropriate controller. 
@@@ 1902 number of memories
This is the number of memories that curves will
be stored or accumulated into. How this number 
is used is determined by the current Data 
Acquisition Mode.
@@@ 1903 detector temp (mention locked)
This is the temperature in degrees C. that the cooler
on the detector head will try to reach and maintain.
The colder the temperature, the better the dark
current value will be. Unless your detector is the
Cryo-CCD detector, cooling the detector will require 
water flow. Refer to the detector manual for
more information.
@@@ 1904 number of scans
This is the number of light-accumulating scans that
will be taken while data acquisition is active. How
this number is used is determined by the current 
Data Acquisition Mode.
@@@ 1905 number of ignored scans
This is the number of scans which will be taken
at the current exposure time, but not used.
This is often used to build a delay into the
data acquisition routine between events. How 
this number is used is determined by the current 
Data Acquisition Mode.
@@@ 1906 source compensation
The Source Compensation value is an extra analog
input value that you can use to compensate for
variations in the light source during the exposure.
The analog value input at the SOURCE COMP IN connec-
tor is converted to digital format and stored with 
each curve. 

You may choose to integrate the Source Comp input 
while the detector is integrating, or you may choose
to sample the input at the end of the exposure time.
If you choose to integrate, different time constants
may be selected to control the sensitivity and satur-
ation level of the source comp channel.
@@@ 1907 Exposure Time
This is the amount of time that light will be gathered 
during one complete scan of the detector element. 
The exposure time depends on many different parameters
such as the type of detector element, the scan setup,
and others. Note that this field automatically prevents
you from entering an exposure time outside of the
acceptable minimum and maximum time limits. This is
a scaled field, so to enter 100 milliseconds, for 
example, type 100m.
@@@ 1908 Keep Clean (Run/Setup)
The keep clean function runs whenever data is not
being acquired. This function continuously reads 
and discards signal from the array to prevent dark
current buildup between acquisitions.

The two modes for this function are:
  Normal - selects the keep clean version that 
    uses the scan pattern you set up. The drawback
    is that there may be a delay after the acquisition
    is "started" until the current keep clean frame 
    is completed.
  Fast - selects the keep clean version mode that
    reads and discards signal as quickly as possible.
    The disadvantage is an effect called reciprocity
    which is discussed in the manual.
@@@ 1909 Trigger Source (Run/Setup)
The trigger source for the pulser may be from
an external voltage input (ETI connector), 
an optical input (OTI connector), or via an 
internal signal which generates a trigger upon
demand. The selection here determines where 
the program will expect the trigger to appear.
The choices are:
  Disable  - all triggers are turned off.
  Internal - internal trigger source.
  Optical  - optical trigger input (OTI).
  /Slope   - external electrical input (ETI),
             rising edge is active at threshold.
  \Slope   - external electrical input (ETI),
             falling edge is active at threshold.
@@@ 1910 Intensifier Mode (Run/Setup)
The intensifier can be set in either gated or
CW mode. In gated mode, no high voltage is 
applied to the intensifier unless a gate pulse
is received. In CW mode, the high voltage is 
always on so that light can always reach the
detector. Be aware that while the intensifier
mode can be controlled via the program, the 
override switch on the gate module can be used
to force the intensifier into CW mode.
@@@ 1911 Delay Inc/Scan (Run/Setup)
The delay between the trigger input and the
pulse generation can be incremented on each
successive pulse output. At the start of each
acquisition, the pulse delay is set to the Start
Delay value. On each successive pulse, the 
delay is then incremented. The range is 0 to
13 milliseconds in 1 nanosecond steps.
@@@ 1912 Delay Range (Run/Setup)
The delay range sets the upper limit on
delay incrementation. This setting interacts
with the "Memories" parameter so that the 
number of memories is adjusted to insure 
that the entire delay range will be swept 
through. Likewise, if the "Memories" value 
is changed when the delay increment is greater
than zero, the delay range will be adjusted. 

Note: An error will occur if you attempt to
set a delay range without previously setting
a non-zero delay increment.
@@@ 1913 
Help message 1913 used by 2000.
@@@ 1914 
Help message 1914 used by 2000.
@@@ 1915
Help message 1915 used by 2000.
@@@ 1916 Start Delay (Run/Setup)
The start delay is the time delay between
the receipt of a trigger (optical, internal,
or external voltage) and the output of the
pulse to the intensifier. The range is 0 to
13 milliseconds in 1 nanosecond steps. 
Because this a scaled parameter field, 
you can enter a 100 millisecond delay by 
keying in 100m; a 100 nanosecond delay 
by keying in 100n.
@@@ 1917 Pulser Width (Run/Setup)
The pulser width determines the length
of time the intensifier will be gated on.
The minimum pulse width depends on the 
intensifier connected; currently the minimum
is 5 ns. The maximum pulse width is 10 ms.
@@@ 1918 
Help message 1918 used by 2000.
@@@ 1919 Cooler On/Off
This toggle field is used to 
turn the cooler on or off.
@@@ 1920 Trigger Cnt (Run/Setup)
The Pulser/Timer board in the detector is 
able to send several pulses at a given delay
before stepping to the next increment. What
this means is that you can specify multiple
triggers per scan. This will increase the 
effective exposure time by repeatedly gating
the intensifier open before reading out the
array. You can specify up to 65535 pulses; 
however, the actual number possible depends
on the exposure time and the pulser width.

Note: Exposure time, pulser width, and 
trigger count are interrelated parameters. 
A change in one can affect the other two.
Refer to the manual for more information. 
@@@ 1921 Audio (Run/Setup)
The audio setting refers to the beeper on
the detector's Pulser/Timer board. This beeper
will sound whenever a pulse is output to the
gate module unless it is turned off here.

Note: This setting has no effect on the light
overload warning sound from the intensifier
gate module. 
@@@ 1922 Trigger Level (Run/Setup)
The OMA4000 program has incorporated 
threshold values for three different kinds of
external electrical trigger input (ETI) 
sources. In addition, you can key in a level 
in the range of -5 volts to +5 volts.

The threshold value determines when the voltage
swing from steady state will trigger the pulser.
The "Trigger Source" of \Slope or /Slope is used
to determine if this will happen on the negative-
or positive-going transition. The thresholds are: 
   TTL   -  +631.3 millivolts.
   NIM F -  -294.5 volts.
   NIM S -  +1.1 volts.
   Volts -  keyboard entry of -5 to +5 volts.
@@@ 1923 Volts (Run/Setup)
This field reports the threshold voltage for the
currently selected source. If none of the 
standard levels are appropriate, you can also
use this field to change to a threshold level
within the range of -5 to +5 volts. Simply key 
in the new trigger level voltage and press 
<Enter>. Note that the parameter label to 
the left of this field will change to "Volts". 
@@@1924 Start Memory (Run/Setup)
This field is used to set the starting memory
location for data acquisition and plotting. The
default, 1, means data will be written to and 
read from the beginning of available memory.
Setting this field to 2 will cause acquisition
and plotting to skip a memory area equal to the
size of one curve.  Any data in that area will 
not be affected. If Start Memory is later set
back to one, the tracks in memory 1 may be
plotted, saved to disk, etc.  Start memory may 
be set from 1 to the value of Max.
@@@ 1925 Da Mode Name
This field gives the name of the currently selected 
DA mode.  This name is the name given with the
DAC_BLOCK statement in the source file for the
DA mode.  You may toggle through all of the 
available DA modes using this field, and select
the desired one by pressing Enter.
@@@ 2000 
Help message 2000 used by 2000.
@@@ 2001
Help message 2001 used by 2000.
@@@ 2002
Help message 2002 used by 2000.
@@@ 2003 
Help message 2003 used by 2000.
@@@ 2004 synchronization
The synchronization selected determines when the
array will be scanned. The synchronizations 
are:
   Internal (Normal) - Scanning is continuous, with
      each scan immediately following the completion
      of the previous scan. 
   External - Scanning is synchronized to an external
      trigger received at the Sync Input connector on
      the Scan Control card.
@@@ 2005 
Help message 2005 used by 2000.
@@@ 2100 Pixel Time
The Pixel Time is the time it takes to scan a pixel.
The actual time corresponding to the Fast, Slow or
Normal (if present) options will vary according to 
the detector type. Values for one type of CCD array
are 10 æs for Fast and 18 æs for slow.
The shorter times have the disadvantage of higher noise.
@@@ 2102 Shift Time
The Shift Time is the time it takes to shift a row of
charge into the CCD shift register. The actual time 
corresponding to the Normal, Slow, or Fast (if present) 
options will vary according to the detector type. Lower 
charge transfer efficiency may be noticeable with the 
faster shift times at lower temperatures.
@@@ 2200 preparation frames
Enter the number of preparation frames to be taken
and discarded before actually beginning to take and
store data. 
@@@ 2201 Shutter Sync
The source for the Shutter Sync signal may be either
Internal or External. If Don't Wait is chosen for a
shutter action, the Shutter Sync signal for that
action is generated internally by the detector.
@@@ 2202 Sync Open
You may choose to have the detector wait 
for a Shutter Sync signal before opening.
@@@ 2203 Sync Close
You may choose to have the detector wait 
for a Shutter Sync signal before closing.
@@@ 2205 shutter normal/forced (CCD)
The CCD shutter can be allowed to operate normally
or it can be forced to open and remain open or to
close and remain closed. When the shutter operates
normally, it opens and closes as instructed by the
Data Acquisition mode and the shutter synchronization.
When the shutter is forced open or forced closed, it
remains in that position in spite of the acquisition
mode and shutter synchronization until it is returned
to normal operation.
@@@ 2206 source compensation
The Source Compensation value is an extra analog
input value that you can use to compensate for
variations in the light source during the exposure.
The analog value input at the SOURCE COMP IN connec-
tor is converted to digital format and stored with 
each curve. 

You may choose to integrate the Source Comp input 
while the detector is integrating, or you may choose
to sample the input at the end of the exposure time.
If you choose to integrate, different time constants
may be selected to control the sensitivity and satur-
ation level of the source comp channel.
@@@ 2300 plot title
The text entered into this field will be used
as the title of the plot. It will be centered
on the top of the plot area.
@@@ 2301 X axis label (Plot Setup)
This is an optional label for the X axis. Note that
the units for this axis are selected in another field,
so it is not necessary to enter the units here.
@@@ 2302 X axis min value (Plot Setup)
Enter the minimum value for the X axis. This may 
be modified if autoscaling is active.
@@@ 2303 X axis max value (Plot Setup)
Enter the maximum value for the X axis. This may
be modified if autoscaling is active.
@@@ 2304 X axis units (Plot Setup)
Select the units most appropriate for what the 
X axis represents, if the default shown is not 
applicable.
@@@ 2305 orientation
"Left" or "Right" refers to the viewer perspective 
