@@@ 3104 Shift mode 
Selects the type of detector array readout.  The 
four types of readout are:
   Tracks Parallel with Serial Register -
      The spectra are assumed to be parallel to
      rows on the array. The serial register is
      parallel to the tracks or spectra.
   Tracks Perpendicular to Serial Register - The
      array is rotated 90 degrees and the spectra 
      are assumed to be parallel to rows on the 
      array. The serial register is perpendicular 
      to the tracks or spectra.
   Masked (lower) - The portion of the array
      furthest from the serial register is masked.
      Set the track height to be equal to the
      height of the unmasked region. Tracks are
      read with the shutter open, so the only delay
      between tracks is the exposure time. This 
      mode imitates a linear photodiode array. 
   Masked (upper) - The portion of the array
      closest to the serial register is masked.
      Set the track height to be equal to the height
      of the unmasked region. When the shutter opens,
      tracks are shifted from the unmasked region into 
      the masked region until it is full. Then the
      shutter is closed and the masked region is read
      out. The only delay between tracks is thus the
      time to shift one track into the masked area.
      This mode imitates a streak camera. 
@@@ 3105 ActiveX
ActiveX refers to the number of active pixels on the 
Detector along a line parallel to the shift register. 
Do not change this number unless you have a non-standard
detector which is not recognized by the software. 
@@@ 3106 ActiveY
ActiveY refers to the number of active pixels on the 
Detector along a line perpendicular to the shift 
register. Do not change this number unless you have
a non-standard detector which is not recognized by
the software. 
@@@ 3107 Anti-Bloom
Selects the amount of antiblooming protection. At 
100%%, the shift register is cleaned every time a 
line is shifted into it (before and after the region
of interest defined by Y0, Rows/Track, and #Tracks.)
Other values cause the shift register to be cleaned
less often, so it accumulates more charge between 
the times it is cleaned. If the dark current or
light signal in the image area is high, the shift
register can accumulate too much charge if it is 
not cleaned for every shift, and some charge spills
into the image area. This is called blooming.
Selecting values less than 100%% can speed up the 
array readout considerably if the region of interest
is small, but at higher light levels this may cause 
blooming from the shift register into the image area.
The antibloom control has less effect as the region
of interest increases in size.
@@@ 3108 Shift Register.
Some detector arrays have more than one shift register 
or may be operated in a dual interlaced mode. Use this 
field to select which one is used. If you use a shift
register other than the default, you may have to swap 
the endpoints of the X or Y axis in the plot menu in
order to see the data in the same orientation as it is 
presented by the default shift register.
@@@ 3109 Streak Mode
Set Streak Mode to On to enable Streak Camera sequencing
for all DA modes which check the Streak Mode flag.  Set 
Streak Mode to Off to disable Streak Camera sequencing.

A CCD detector may be used to emulate a streak camera.
Some portion of the CCD array should be masked off, 
preferably by applying an opaque coating directly to
the sensor surface.  Then multiple images of the un-
masked portion can be shifted rapidly under the mask.
The sequence of events is:

  1. Open shutter if it is not already open.
  2. Shift unmasked portion under the mask
     multiple times.
  3. Close the shutter.
  4. Read the stored data under the mask
     into memory.

Note that the normal Exposure Time sequence does not
occur.  Instead, the Exposure Time setting on the Run
Setup Menu is used to determine the amount of time
between each shifting of the exposed area.  Also, the
Wait For Sync Before field on the Run Setup Menu can
be turned on to cause the detector to wait for external
sync signals before each shift of the exposed area.

See the help for the Rows Exposed setting for more info.
@@@ 3110 Rows Exposed
When Streak Mode is On, this field is used to tell the 
program how many rows of the CCD are exposed (i.e. not
under the mask).  The minimum number for this is 1 row
exposed, and the maximum number is « of the number of
rows on the entire CCD.  When a valid number is entered
in this field, and if Streak Mode has been turned on, the 
proper values for #Tracks, Starts at Row, and Rows in Track
are automatically calculated and entered into the correct
places on this menu.
@@@ 3111 Start at Column
