@@@ 3121 RowsExposed Set
The settings for #Tracks, Start Row, and Rows in Track have
been set to correspond to the normal requirements for the
setting you have chosen.  You may need to adjust these for
your particular experiment.
@@@ 3122 Rows Exposed with no streakmode
Streak mode is not enabled.  For the Rows Exposed setting to
have any effect, you should enable Streak Mode first.
@@@ 3200  Baseline Actions (Baseline)
These actions operate on the whole baseline curve:
   Clear - Deletes all knots, destroys the baseline.
   Autogenerate from Z - Generates a new baseline
      based on curve Z. 25 knots are generated,
      about equally spaced along the X axis but at
      local curve minima.
   Increase by Z - Adds the value of Z to every knot
      of the baseline. This makes the entire 
      baseline larger by Z.
   Decrease by Z - Subtracts the value of Z from 
      every knot of the baseline. This makes the
      entire baseline smaller by Z.
@@@ 3201 Z (Baseline)
Z is the value used by Increase/Decrease to
add/subtract to the baseline. It is also the Z-axis
curve number to be displayed when displaying one
curve only.
@@@ 3202 Threshold (Baseline)
Enter the Threshold value. This value is used by the
curve drawing functions that draw 'baseline w/peaks' 
and 'zero w/peaks'. A "peak" is any point on a curve
that exceeds the baseline curve by at least the value
of Threshold.
@@@ 3203 Save to: (Baseline)
Enter the filename to be used when storing the 
displayed curve/s. These curves will be saved to
the named curve when <Enter> is pressed. If the
curve already exists, they are appended at the end.
If the curve file doesn't exist, a new one is created.
@@@ 3204 Display Curve (Baseline)
"X" means plot the actual curve data on the screen.
" " means do NOT plot the actual curve data. 

All displayed curves will be saved when the
Save To function is used. 
@@@ 3205 Baseline Draw
"X" means plot the baseline on the screen.
" " means do NOT plot the baseline. 

All displayed curves will be saved when the 
Save To function is used.
@@@ 3206 Baseline w/peaks
"X" means plot the 'baseline with peaks' curve.
" " means do NOT plot 'baseline with peaks' curve.

The curve plotted is equal to the baseline curve at
all points where the data curve is less than
Threshold above the baseline. It is equal to the
data curve at those points where the data curve is
at least as great as Threshold + the baseline curve. 
All displayed curves will be saved when the Save To
function is used.
@@@ 3207 Zero w/peaks
"X" means plot the 'zero with peaks' curve.
" " means do NOT plot 'zero with peaks' curve.

The curve plotted is equal to zero at all points
where the data curve is less than Threshold above
the baseline. It is equal to the data curve
minus the baseline at those points where the data
curve is at least as great as Threshold + the 
baseline curve. All displayed curves will be 
saved when the Save To function is used.
@@@ 3208 One Z only
" " means that all curves will be drawn.
"X" means that only one Z-axis curve will be
    drawn. 

All displayed curves will be saved when the
Save To function is used.
@@@ 3209 Select (Baseline)
Use to add new knots to the baseline. Position
the cursor at the desired location for the new
knot and press enter. Up to 30 knots can be 
used to construct a baseline. Use <F10> to exit.
@@@ 3210 Delete (Baseline)
Deletes a knot from the baseline. The knot
deleted is the last knot highlighted before
leaving the knots list.
@@@ 3300 Live to Disk Filename
Enter the filename to be used by the program
when a Live to Disk data acquisition is performed.
The acquired data is automatically stored to the 
named file on disk. 

Unless this name is changed before each Live to 
Disk acquisition, subsequent Live to Disk curves
will overwrite the existing data. 
@@@ 3301 # of Repetitions
Enter the number of repetitions to be acquired and
stored in the named Live to Disk file. The number
of repetitions tells the program how many times data 
acquisition is to be run when "Go" is activated. It
can run once (1 repetition) or it can be run more 
than once ("n" repetitions). The number of curves
acquired depends on the Run setup and the number
of repetitions. 
@@@ 3302 Mode Normal/Fast (GPIB AT)
Unless there is an AT-GPIB installed in the
host computer, the mode of data transfer will
be Normal. If there is an AT-GPIB, the data
transfer can be sped up by selecting Fast. 
@@@ 3303 Go
Starts the Live to Disk acquisition.

@@@ 3500 Live Capture Filename
Enter the filename to be used by the program when
a Live Capture (Alt-F5) is performed. The captured 
data is stored in the host computer's memory with 
that name. Storing the data to disk is done via the 
Curve Directory. 

Unless the filename is changed before each capture,
subsequent captured curves will also be stored in 
this curve set. The new data does not overwrite the
existing data; instead, it is inserted at the start
of the curve set. 
@@@ 3501 Capture Mode
Live curves can be displayed and captured singly 
or in a set of curves. Select the type of display/
capture mode desired from the following options:
   Single Curve (Fast) - Displays the number of 
      memories set in the Run/Setup screen. One
      curve is captured at a time when <F5> is
      pressed.
   Multiple Curve (Slow) - Displays the number of
      memories set in the Run/Setup screen. 
      A set of memories is captured when <F5>
      is pressed. These memories (curves) may or
      may not be from the same run. To guarantee
      that the curves are from the same run, use
      <Fl> Pause/Next and then <F5> Capture.
@@@ 3502 Live Filter Mode
During Live or Live-B display, a "filter" can be
applied to the data so that it will be displayed 
in terms of absorbance or in radiometric units.
@@@ 3503 Live Filter Mode
During Live or Live-B display, a "filter" can be
applied to the data so that it will be displayed 
in terms of absorbance or in radiometric units.
This field selects the name of the curve set to
be used as the "reference" for the absorbance or
radiometric correction.  It must be a curve set
which is already in memory. You can choose from
a list of curvesets in memory by pressing the
Alt-F1 key combination, select the desired set
from the list, and pressing the Enter Key.
If lastlive is chosen as the reference, the program
will copied it from the detector into a tempfile
curveset so it may be used as a reference without
being overwritten when data acquisition begins.
@@@ 3504 Reload Live for Reference
lastlive cannot be used directly as a reference,
since it is overwritten when new data is acquired.
Instead, the data in lastlive will be copied into
a new curve set. (Press the Enter Key)
@@@ 3505 Set Dual Track Absorbance
In Dual Track Live Absorbance Display, the first
track on the display uses the first track on the
CCD as a signal and the second track on the CCD
as a reference.  The second track on the display
uses the second track of the CCD as a signal and
the first track as a reference. (Press ENTER)
@@@ 3600 Accum Set Name (Accum)
Enter the filename to be used by the program when
an Accum data acquisition is performed. The 
acquired data is stored in the host computer's 
memory with that name. Storing the data to disk is
done via the Curve Directory. 

Unless this name is changed before each Accum 
acquisition, subsequent data will also be stored in
this curve set. This new data does not overwrite the
existing data; instead, it is inserted at the start 
of the curve set. 
@@@ 3700 Keystroke file name
Enter the file name which is to be 
used to store recorded macros, or
to execute previously stored macros.
@@@ 3701 Keystroke play or record
Choose to record a new Keystroke macro 
or to play back a previously stored macro.
@@@ 3702 Keystroke delay
Enter a delay value in seconds. This
value will affect the playback speed.
@@@ 3703 Keystroke Go
Starts the Keystroke recording or play back.
@@@ 3800 Set cursor X goto value
Enter the X axis value that you want
the graph cursor to jump to. 
@@@ 3801 Set cursor Z goto value
Enter the Z axis value (displayed curve 
number) that you want the graph cursor 
to jump to. 
@@@ 3802 Cursor Jump Go
Set the graph cursor to the requested
X and Z values.
@@@ 3900 Tag Curves starting curve
Enter the Z axis value of the first curve to
be tagged.
@@@ 3901 Tag Curves curve number increment 
Enter the integer tagging interval for the set
of curves to be tagged. 1 means every curve,
2 means every other curve, 3 means every third
curve, etc.
@@@ 3902 Tag Curves go
Tag all the curves specified by the starting Z
value and the tagging interval up to the number of
curves currently displayed in the window.
@@@ 3903 Copy Tag Curves Name
Enter a name for the curve set which will be 
created from the displayed tagged curves. If this 
curve set already exists it may be overwritten.
@@@ 3903 Copy Tag Curves Go
Copy the displayed tagged curves to the curve 
directory using the entered name. If this 
curve set already exists it may be overwritten.
@@@ 4000 Number of Regions
Enter the number of regions for each curve.  Each
region may have a different Start Pixel, End Pixel,
and Region Exposure Time.  This allows you to skip
the signal on parts of the detector, and also to
integrate the signal on different parts of the detector
@@@ 4001 Base Exposure Time
This field is the same as the Exposure Time field on
the Run Setup menu.  All Region Exposure Times must
be "power of 2 fractions" of the Base Exposure time,
e.g. 1/2, 1/4, 1/8, etc.  At least one region must have
a Region Exposure Time equal to the Base Exposure Time.
@@@ 4002 ActiveX
This refers to the number of active pixels on the 
detector. Do not change this number unless you have a 
non-standard detector which is not recognized by the 
software. 
@@@ 4003 Region X0
Enter the starting pixel number for this region.  Regions
cannot overlap.
@@@ 4004 Region End Pixel
Enter the ending pixel number for this region.  Regions
must have at least 8 pixels and cannot overlap.
@@@ 4005 Region Exposure Time
Enter the time for this region to be integrated before
being read out and reset. All Region Exposure Times must 
be "power of 2 fractions" of the Base Exposure time, e.g. 
1/2, 1/4, 1/8, etc.  At least one region must have a Region 
Exposure Time equal to the Base Exposure Time.
@@@ 5100 Lamp Data File
You may specify the name of a lamp data file to load.  The
lamp data file specifies the output of the standard lamp 
at specific wavelengths.  This data is normally supplied by 
the lamp manufacturer.  Combining the lamp data with a lamp
curve produces a correction curve, which may be used to cal-
ibrate data in radiometric units. The lamp data file has the 
format:

LAMP DATA
LAMP UNITS #
xxx1   yyy1
xxx2   yyy2
 .      .
 .      .
 .      .

The first two lines in the file must be LAMP DATA and 
LAMP UNITS. The number at the end of the second line is 0 
for COUNTS, 1 for COUNTS/SEC, and 2 for microwatts/nm/cm2.
Following lines contain up to 100 pairs of wavelength and
intensity values.
You may also enter the lamp data directly, by using the 
ADD key and entering the desired values under the Wavelen.
and Value fields.
@@@ 5101 Lamp Units
This should be set to the value of the desired calibration
units.  If the lamp data are read from a file, the units
are automatically set to the correct value.
@@@ 5102 Load or Save Lamp Data
Select this field to load or save lamp data from an ASCII
file.  See help for the Lamp Data File field for more
information about this file. You may also enter the lamp 
data directly, by using the ADD key and entering the desired 
values under the Wavelen. and Value fields.
@@@ 5103 Lamp Curve Set
Enter here the name of a curve set which contains data
acquired by exposing the detector to the standard lamp.   
Once a lamp curve set is selected and lamp data have been
loaded or entered, a correction curve may be generated.
@@@ 5104 Correction Curve
Enter here a new name for the correction curve set.  Using
the Apply field will create this curve set, using the data
from the standard lamp data file and the lamp curve set
you specified in the fields above.  The correction curve may
be used to convert subsequently acquired curve sets into 
radiometric units, such as microwatts/nm/cm2.  The formula
for doing so is:
                    Raw Data       
  Calibrated data = --------  * Correction Curve 
                       ET          
where ET is the exposure time of the Raw Data.
@@@ 5105 Create Correction Curve
Selecting this field causes the Correction curve to be
created, if you have loaded or entered lamp data and
specified both a Lamp Curve and a Correction curve set.
@@@ 5106 Apply to Curve
This field is not yet implemented.  To calibrate data, 
use the Math - Calculate form to perform the correction
operation, which is:
                    Raw Data       
  Calibrated data = --------  * Correction Curve 
                       ET          
where ET is the exposure time of the Raw Data.
@@@ 5107 Apply
This field is not yet implemented.  To calibrate data, 
use the Math - Calculate form to perform the correction
operation, which is:
                    Raw Data       
  Calibrated data = --------  * Correction Curve 
                       ET          
where ET is the exposure time of the Raw Data.
@@@ 5108 Add Lamp Data
Selecting this field will cause a new Wavelen/Value pair
to be added to the lamp data list to the right.  The
initial value of the new pair will be 0, 0, but you can
then edit the pair to enter the new correct values.
@@@ 5109 Delete Lamp Data
Selecting this field will delete the Wavelen/Value pair
last highlighted in the list to the right.
@@@ 5110 Wavelength value
Here you may change the wavelength at which the lamp
intensity value on the right was observed.  These values
should normally come from a data sheet supplied by the
manufacturer of the lamp.
@@@ 5111 Intensity value
Here you may change the wavelength at which the lamp
intensity value on the right was observed.  These values
should normally come from a data sheet supplied by the
manufacturer of the lamp.
Here you may change the intensity of the lamp observed
at the wavelength on the left.  These values should 
normally come from a data sheet supplied by the
manufacturer of the lamp.
@@@ 3400 Macro Menu (Command Line)
The two lines at the bottom of the screen, which
appear when Alt-F10 is pressed, allow you to exe-
cute macro commands. The upper line is where you
type the commands, and the lower line is where
user interaction occurs, via the READLN and 
WRITELN macros.

